  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Matching the Rhymes of a Poem at the Huigyeong Pavilion
  author: Lee Dal-chung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through all the ages, how many capitals have risen and fallen?
    What once united scattered, what once scattered gathered again.
    Heaven's will forever turns toward those possessed of virtue—
    why should the spirit of earth bear such shame in silence?

    Near the Xinglun Temple, the bell's voice resonates deep,
    while from steep Duanshi Mountain floats the gleam of ancient swords.
    I dare not follow Sima Xiangru's inscription on the pillar,
    yet can we not say that Zhong Xuan ascends the tower to ease his heart?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Sima Xiangru was a Han dynasty poet famous for his literary inscriptions; the reference suggests ambitious literary pretensions
  - key: ''
    value: Zhong Xuan (中宣) may refer to a figure seeking solace or expressing emotion from an elevated vantage point, echoing the tower setting
